#Text=Kuranda
#Text=Kuranda is a small town in Far North Queensland adjoining the Barron Gorge National Park .
#Text=It 's only around half an hour to drive from Cairns , and the scenic trip by train or SkyRail makes an extremely popular day trip .
#Text=The village and markets are overflowing with visitors during the middle of each day .
#Text=Get in
#Text=Drive from Cairns via the Captain Cook and Kennedy Highways .
#Text=The trip takes approximately 40 minutes .
#Text=You can access the most scenic points on the railway journey by car also , including the Barron Falls railway platform .
#Text=Hop on the Kuranda Scenic Railway for a ( very ) leisurely one- and a half hour trip 329 meters up and 34 kilometers out from Cairns .
#Text=Two services daily in each direction .
#Text=One-way $ 50 , return $ 76 , reservations recommended .
#Text=Child and family rates do apply .
#Text=Services depart from Cairns Central Station , close to the centre of Cairns and stop at Freshwater station along the way .
#Text=Freshwater is convenient if you are coming from Port Douglas and the north .
#Text=This is a scenic and historic journey rather than a utilitarian means of transport , and is priced accordingly .
#Text=The train carriages are not air-conditioned .
#Text=Catch the Skyrail Rainforest Cableway .
#Text=This is a gondola ride through the rainforest treetops , with a couple of stops on route to change cars .
#Text=Great views of the rainforest canopy .
#Text=As of November 2016 , are :
#Text=One-way is $ 50 adults and $ 25 children , return is $ 75 adults and $ 37.50 children .
#Text=A one-way Skyrail , one-way Kuranda
#Text=Railway package is $ 109.50 adults and $ 54.75 children , with transfers back Smithfield/Freshwater at additional cost .
#Text=The base station is around 15km north of Cairns , around half-way to Kuranda .
#Text=Transfers from both Cairns , Cairns Beaches and Port Douglas are available .
#Text=A 5 % discount is available when you book online .
#Text=The local buses service the Skyrail base station from Cairns every hour or so .
#Text=There is a large , free carpark at the Skyrail base station .
#Text=There are two bus companies that run scheduled bus services between Cairns and Kuranda .
#Text=If you just want to get to Kuranda they will save you time and money over the scenic alternatives , taking only 40 minutes for the trip , and costing $ 6.70 per adult ( as of November 2016 ) .
#Text=Trans North bus makes several trips daily , and the timetables are on their website .
#Text=Many people combine the Kuranda Scenic railway and the skyrail , travelling to Kuranda on one and returning on the other .

#Text=From the scenery point of view , take the railway first in the morning and after that make the Skyrail trip - take your time to stop and look around in the Rainforestation on the way back to the coast .
#Text=After arriving at the coast side ( great views ) , you have the opportunity to visit the Tjapukai village to learn something about the Aboriginal culture .
#Text=You can book both directions through either service , but if you are booking late , you may have to book separately as they allocate each other a limited number of seats .
#Text=Combining the two is more expensive , both in terms of time and money .
#Text=They both offer significant discounts for taking their service both ways , and only small discounts for combining the two .
#Text=In addition getting from the Skyrail base station back to Cairns station is another logistical hassle , or additional cost if you pay for the transfers .

#Text=If you want to do the round trip with the Skyrail and the train and do n't feel like coordinating with local buses , there are a number of tour companies that package that journey for you , including tickets and transfers .
#Text=If you are travelling up to Kuranda with luggage , bear in mind that neither the Skyrail nor the railway cater for large amounts of luggage .
#Text=The Skyrail will not carry any luggage at all , and the amount is strictly limited to what will fit in the luggage space in the passenger compartment on the train .
#Text=There is no problem with prams and daypacks , but neither of these methods of transport may be suitable if you are doing more than a day trip to Kuranda .
#Text=Get around
#Text=Kuranda is a small village , although somewhat hilly .
#Text=Walking about 1km will take you from one end of town to the other .
#Text=Do n't count on being able to walk quickly , as the streets tend to be packed with people .
#Text=A one-way courtesy bus between the Skyrail and scenic railway stations at the south end of town and the wildlife attractions at the north of town .
#Text=The bus departs every twenty minutes , but most people walk the distance .
#Text=See
#Text=Birdworld , ☏ +61740939188 , ✉ sales@birdworldkuranda.com .
#Text=Daily 9am-4pm except Christmas Day .
#Text=Heritage Markets , Rob Vievers Drive .
#Text=Birdworld is a large mesh canopy , open to natural light in which you can wander among free flying birds armed with an identification sheet to pick them out .
#Text=The birds are divided evenly between colourful parrots and drab quails and doves with the addition of some cassowaries fenced away from people wandering around the circuit .
#Text=Entry is $ 14 for adults , $ 5 children and $ 29 for families with two adults and 2 children .
#Text=A combined pass with the butterfly sanctuary and the Koala Gardens is $ 33 adults and $ 16 children .
#Text=Adults $ 18 , children $ 9 .
#Text=Kuranda Koala Gardens , ☏ +61740939953 , ✉ info@cairnstropicalzoo.com .
#Text=Heritage Markets , Rob Vievers Drive .
#Text=The Koala Gardens is a small wildlife zoo housing Australian native animals .
#Text=In addition to koalas there are kangaroos , crocodiles , snakes and lizards .
#Text=Visitors can hold a koala and have their picture taken .
#Text=Entry is $ 14 for adults , $ 7 for children .
#Text=Photo holding a koala will be an extra $ 15 .
#Text=The kangaroos and wallabies are tame and friendly and you can grab a free handful or two of feed at the entrance to their lawn .
#Text=Australian Butterfly Sanctuary , 8 Rob Vievers Drive , ☏ +61740937575 , fax : +61740938923 , ✉ ulysses@australianbutterflies.com .
#Text=The butterfly sanctuary is an aviary containing rainforest butterflies - Birdwings Ulysees and more , its great for Kids .
#Text=Open 9:45AM to 4:30PM , with guided tours from 10:00 to 3:15PM .
#Text=Wear bright colored clothing to get the butterflies to land on you .
#Text=Rainforestation Nature Park , Kennedy Highway , ☏ +61740855008 .
#Text=This award-winning attraction is situated five minutes from Kuranda Village .
#Text=Experience the tropical rainforest on both land and water aboard an amphibious World War II Army Duck .
#Text=Learn about aboriginal culture with the Pamagirri Aboriginal Experience , including a traditional dance performance and boomerang throwing , spear throwing and didgeridoo playing .
#Text=See native Australian animals including kangaroos , koalas , crocodiles , wombats , dingoes and the cassowary .
#Text=Honey House Kuranda , 7 Therwine Street , ☏ +61 740-937261 .
#Text=Established in 1959 , Honey House Kuranda continues to offer tourists the chance to see live bees working hard to make honey and to sample over 20 North Qld premium raw honey varieties .
#Text=There is also fresh honeycomb , medicinal honeys and beauty products all made with the highest quality honey .
#Text=free .
#Text=Skeleton Creek
